Ford Go Bike Dataset Exploration¶

by Xola¶

Introduction¶

I am going to look at a dataset titled '201902_fordgobike_tripdata.csv' with 183412 rows and 16 columns this dataset has interesting columns such as start and end station of each trip, bike id, and type of user (customer and subscriber).

#change member birth year to interger instead of float

#noticing that "bike_id is not the first column and so we will rearrange some columns"

def reorder_columns(columns, first_cols=['bike_id','start_time','end_time','duration_sec']):
    columns = list(set(columns) - set(first_cols))
    new_order = first_cols + columns
    return new_order

Dataset structure¶

The dataset has 183412 rows and 16 features namely ('bike_id','start_time','end_time','duration_sec','start_station_id', 'end_station_id','start_station_name','end_station_longitude','end_station_name','bike_share_for_all_trip','member_birth_year', 'start_station_longitude','member_gender','user_type','start_station_latitude','end_station_latitude')

Main features of interest¶

I am interested to see where the bike activity occurs the most. I would like to know the distribution of gender among the bike users.

Features in the dataset that will support the investigation¶

I believe the start station name and end station name will be the features that reveal the bike activities and the member gender feature should display the comparison among the genders. I think that start time and end time will show the time of day when there is bike activity and the month will show me which months have more bike usage.

#heatmap looking at average duration of gender member and user type

heat_map= birth_year.groupby(['member_gender', 'user_type']).mean()['duration_sec']
heat_map= heat_map.reset_index(name = 'duration_sec_avg')
heat_map= heat_map.pivot(index = 'user_type', columns = 'member_gender',
                            values = 'duration_sec_avg')
sb.heatmap(heat_map, annot = True, fmt = '.2f',
           cbar_kws = {'label' : 'duration mean'});
plt.title('Member gender VS User type through duration');

Male users account for more users than others genders, but interestingly female users spent more time(duration) on average than other genders.

Conclusions¶

Bike ID 5175 is the most used, appearing 172 times in a multitude of start stations. There is a positive relationship between member birth year and duration spent on trips. Given that this dataset is about a bike sharing platform, the bikes(bike_id) are going to be used more than once, but some, such as bike id no 5175 appears to be used much more than other bikes(172 times)
